# Security and Secrets

## Secrets Management
- Never commit API keys, tokens, or secrets to version control.
- Use environment variables (`.env.local`) for sensitive configuration.
- Add `.env.local` to `.gitignore` (verify it's there).
- Document required environment variables in README.

## Data Privacy
- Local storage contains user data; treat as sensitive.
- Don't log sensitive user information to console in production.
- Validate and sanitize all user inputs.
- Consider data encryption for sensitive fields if moving to backend.

## Client-Side Security
- Validate all inputs on client side (but don't rely on it alone).
- Sanitize data before storing in localStorage.
- Use try-catch for localStorage operations (private browsing may block).
- Don't expose internal data structures in error messages.

## Do
- Use environment variables for all secrets.
- Validate and sanitize user inputs.
- Handle localStorage errors gracefully.
- Keep sensitive data out of logs.

## Don't
- Commit secrets to git.
- Trust client-side validation alone.
- Expose internal errors to users.
- Store unvalidated data.

